The '''''General-Admiral''-class''' ships were a pair of [[armored cruiser]]s built for the [[Imperial Russian Navy]] in the early 1870s. They are generally considered as the first true [[armored cruiser]]s.<ref>Beeler, p. 222</ref>

==Design and description==
Originally classified as armored [[corvette]]s, the ''General-Admiral''s were redesignated as semi-[[armored frigate]]s on 24 March 1875. They were laid out as [[Central battery ship|central battery ironclads]] with the armament concentrated amidships.<ref name=w68/>

The ''General-Admiral''-class ships were {{convert|285|ft|10|in|m|1}} [[overall length|long overall]]. They had a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|48|ft|m|1}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|24|ft|5|in|m|1}}. The ships were designed to [[Displacement (ship)|displace]] {{convert|4604|LT|MT}}, but displaced {{convert|5031|LT|MT|}} as built, an increase of over {{convert|400|LT|t}}. The iron-hulled ships were not fitted with a [[Naval ram|ram]] and their crew numbered approximately 482 officers and men.<ref name=w68>Watts, p. 72</ref>

The ships had a [[Marine steam engine#Compound|vertical compound steam engine]] driving a single two-bladed, {{convert|6.25|m|ftin|adj=on|disp=flip}} propeller, using steam provided by [[Scotch marine boiler|cylindrical boilers]]. The number of boilers differed between the sisters. ''General-Admiral'' had five that generated a working pressure of {{convert|60|psi|kPa kg/cm2|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} so that the engine produced {{convert|4772|ihp|lk=in}}. This gave her during a maximum speed around {{convert|12.3|kn|lk=in}} during her [[sea trial]]s. ''Gerzog Edinburgski'' had four boilers and her engine made {{convert|5590|ihp|abbr=on}} that propelled her at {{convert|11.5|kn}}.<ref name=w44>Wright, pp. 44–45</ref>

The ''General-Admiral'' class carried a maximum of {{convert|1000|LT|t}} of coal which gave them an economical range of {{convert|5900|nmi|lk=in}} at a speed of {{convert|10|kn}}. They were [[ship rig|ship]]-rigged with three [[mast (sailing)|mast]]s. To reduce [[drag (physics)|drag]] while under sail, the single [[funnel (ship)|funnel]] was retractable and the propeller could be hoisted into the hull.<ref name=w5>Wright, p. 45</ref>

The sisters also differed in their armament. ''General-Admiral'' had six {{convert|8|in|adj=on|0}}, two {{convert|6|in|adj=on|0}} and four {{convert|87|mm|adj=on|1|sp=us}} [[Rifled breech loader|rifled breech-loading guns]] (RBL). ''Gerzog Edinburgski'' had four 8-inch, five 6-inch and six {{convert|107|mm|adj=on|1|sp=us}} guns.<ref name=s9>Silverstone, p. 359</ref>

The ships had a complete [[waterline]] [[Belt armor|belt]] of [[wrought iron]] that ranged in thickness from 6 inches amidships to {{convert|5|in|0}} at the ends of the ships. The armor had a total height of {{convert|2.15|m|ftin|disp=flip}}, of which {{convert|1.55|m|ftin|disp=flip}} was below the waterline. The central [[Artillery battery#Naval usage|battery]] was also protected by 6-inch armor plates.<ref>Wright, p. 44</ref>

